    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your alternator is the vehicle's heart, and it is responsible for creating the electrical power your car needs to keep running. It takes the engine's mechanical energy and converts it into electricity, which then charges the battery and powers all the electrical systems. If it starts to fail, you will likely notice the battery light on your dashboard, dim headlights, or a strange whining noise coming from the engine bay. To confirm the issue, you can check the battery voltage with a multimeter; a healthy alternator should be outputting around 13.5 to 14.5 volts when the engine is running. If you are experiencing any of these symptoms, it is a good idea to schedule a diagnostic check with a mechanic.",
