    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If your voltage reading is low, the next step is to test the alternator’s output while the engine is running and then inspect the battery terminals and wiring for corrosion or loose connections. You can also check the alternator’s belt tension, as a slipping belt can cause voltage drops. As for “electrical gremlins,” that’s just a fun way to describe intermittent wiring issues, often caused by loose connectors, worn-out connectors, or moisture intrusion. It’s not a supernatural cause, but rather a mechanical one that can be diagnosed with a good multimeter and a careful inspection of the wiring harness.",
